50|$|Governmental {{policies}} often {{reflect the}} tension between two contrasting types of language ideologies: <b>ideologies</b> <b>that</b> conceive of language as a resource, problem, or right and <b>ideologies</b> <b>that</b> conceive of language as pluralistic phenomena. The language-related policies that emerge in such instances often reflect the compromise that is reached between {{these two types of}} ideologies. According to Blommaert and Verschueren, this compromise is often reinterpreted as a single, unified ideology, evidenced by the many European societies characterized by a language ideological homogenism.|$|R
