40|$|This article {{intends to}} show <b>that</b> <b>ideology</b> is always {{organized}} systemically by undertaking the opposition between conformity and diversity as its fundamental criterion. In order to underpin this hypothesis, {{the present article}} examines the inner structure of five classic <b>ideologies,</b> <b>that</b> {{can be understood as}} ideal ideological types. The analysis reveals <b>that</b> <b>ideologies</b> do not form a system because at the core of any ideology there is a key-concept not determined nor influenced by the key concepts of other ideologie...|$|R
50|$|Integrative models {{acknowledge}} the coexistence of separate group-based identities within a common group identity. This is {{in alignment with}} multicultural <b>ideologies</b> <b>that</b> emphasize appreciation for racial and ethnic diversity while still emphasizing a common national identity.|$|R
